[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    523[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The "the thing I would do differently the second time: start with a narrower set of protocols (the highest-volume routine presentations: upper respiratory infections, skin rashes, urinary symptoms, minor musculoskeletal injuries, common pediatric presentations like fever and ear pain) before expanding to the high-stakes protocols (chest pain, severe headache, abdominal pain, trauma)" earns its position** as the chapter's analog of the self-deprecating-expertise-with-actionable-takeaway register. The narrow-start-validates-the-architecture-before-launching-with-high-acuity-presentations framing is the recipe's strongest single deployment-strategy primitive.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    524[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **The closing "the triage bot is the recipe in this chapter where the operational, clinical, and regulatory engineering most clearly outweighs the ML engineering. The ML engineering is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes; the protocol corpus, the clinical-decision-rule library, the chart-context integration, the regulatory artifact, the medical-director sign-off, the outcome-correlation pipeline, and the per-cohort equity monitoring are the parts that distinguish a clinically-safe deployment from a clinically-dangerous one. Build the institutional muscles for the harder parts first; the bot is the easier part." framing earns its position as the recipe's strongest single closing primitive.** The clinical-and-regulatory-engineering-outweighs-the-ML-engineering thesis is recipe-distinct.
